Add checkstyle to gradleWhile checkstyle is not covered as a learning objective in level 2, itsnabsence makes it harder for maintainers of the repository to ensure thatnthe coding standards are followed, as some violations (such as trailingnwhitespaces and redundant imports) can be difficult to spot unless onenpays a lot of attention to them.nncheckstyle.xml is taken from level 4.n
Fix checkstyle rule violations in main classes
Fix checkstyle rule violations in tests

Generate gradle wrapperThe gradle wrapper has to be generated as Travis is not able tonexecute the checkstyle tasks without facing the following error:nnExecution failed for task ':checkstyleMain'.n> java.lang.ClassNotFoundException:n> com.puppycrawl.tools.checkstyle.CheckStyleTasknnThere were some breaking changes made to checkstyle that causesnincompatibility with older versions of Gradle, such as Gradle 2.2.1,nwhich is used by Travis. (more info about the breaking changes here:nhttps://github.com/checkstyle/checkstyle/issues/2107)nnGenerate the wrapper, which will help to resolve this issue and ensure anstandard gradle version used by everyone.n

[#123] Set up checkstyle (#145)While checkstyle is not covered as a learning objective in level 2, itsrnabsence makes it harder for maintainers of the repository to ensure thatrnthe coding standards are followed, as some violations (such as trailingrnwhitespaces and redundant imports) can be difficult to spot unless onernpays a lot of attention to them.

Move handling of missing file to normal code pathAs stated in the comments of the original code, handling the missingnfile using an exception is not appropriate, because it is a normalnsituation (e.g. when starting the program for the very first time).nnTherefore, handle the logic outside the exception code path to aidnreadability.n
Remove creating new file on load()Saving should not be the job of the load() method. It should have beennhandled by save().nnRemove the saving logic in load().n

Add unit test for loading non-existent filesThe scenario whereby the storage file does not exist is not unitntested.nnThis unit test also ensures that the non-existent file is notnimmediately created when it tries to load from that file (which shouldnnot be the behaviour of load()).n

[#129] StorageFile class: load method should not create a new file (#142)load() method creates a new address book xml file if itrndoes not exist.rnrnHowever, the responsibility of load() is to simply read the file,rnnot write it. Even if the file does not exist, load() should simplyrntreat the situation as if it is loading a blank file, and handlernaccordingly. Creating a new file is redundant anyway if load() doesrnnot even attempt to read it after creation, and load() will not gainrnany new information by reading it.rnrnLet's remove the saving functionality of load() in order to narrowrndown the responsibility of the method to purely just reading the xmlrnfiles.

AddressBook: remove unused addTag()AddressBook#addTag() adds a Tag to the master list of Tags innAddressBook.nnThis method is not used anywhere, and can be classified as unused code.nThere are no commands that support the addition of Tags only, and it isnalso not part of any learning objectives. Furthermore,nAddressBook#syncTagsWithMasterList() already handles the addition ofnTags from a Person gracefully without using exceptions. It should benremoved as unused code contributes to maintenance and comprehensionnoverheads.nnLet's remove AddressBook#addTag().n

UniqueTagList: remove unused add()UniqueTagList#add() adds a Tag to the list of unique Tags, and throws annexception if it is a duplicate of an existing Tag in the list.nnWith the removal of AddressBook#addTag(), this method is not usednanywhere, and can be classified as unused code. It should be removed asnunused code contributes to maintenance and comprehension overheads.nnLet's remove UniqueTagList#add().n

AddressBook: remove unused removeTag()AddressBook#removeTag() removes a Tag from the master list of Tags andnfrom any Person in AddressBook.nnThis method is not used anywhere, and can be classified as unused code.nThere are no commands that support the removal of Tags only, and it isnalso not part of any learning objectives. It should be removed as unusedncode contributes to maintenance and comprehension overheads.nnLet's remove AddressBook#removeTag().n

UniqueTagList: remove unused remove()UniqueTagList#remove() removes a Tag from the list of unique Tags, andnthrows an exception if it is not found in the list.nnWith the removal of AddressBook#removeTag(), this method is not usednanywhere, and can be classified as unused code. It should be removed asnunused code contributes to maintenance and comprehension overheads.nnLet's remove UniqueTagList#remove().n

AddressBook: remove unused containsTag()AddressBook#containsTag() checks if the master list of Tags contains anTag with the same value as the given Tag.nnAddressBook#containsTag() is not used in the production code. While itnis used in test code, its use can be replaced bynAddressBookTest#isTagObjectInAddressBookList().nnLet's remove AddressBook#containsTag().nnNotes:n* Why not keep AddressBook#containsTag() and removenAddressBookTest#isTagObjectInAddressBookList() instead? The former doesna value equality test while the latter goes further and does a referencenequality test. The test code requires a reference equality test tonverify Person objects refer to Tag objects in the common tag listninstead of keeping its own copies of Tag objects.n* Why not change AddressBook#containsTag() to use reference equality andnuse that in tests? Doing so will make AddressBook#containsTag()'snsemantics inconsistent with the rest of our API.n

[#169] Addressbook::addTag() is not used  (#179)Let's remove the following methods that are no longer used, rnincluding other related code that are made redundant by rntheir removal.rn* Addressbook#addTag()rn* Addressbook#containsTag()rn* Addressbook#removeTag()rn* UniqueTagList#add()rn* UniqueTagList#remove()

gradle wrapper: upgrade gradle to v4.8.1Synchronize the Gradle version with AddressBook-Level4's.nnThis upgrade was done by running the following command:nn./gradlew wrapper --gradle-version 4.8.1nnand converting the line endings in gradlew.bat to unix to be consistentnwith our conventions.n

build.gradle: mirror formatting of AB-4's build.gradleMake the overall layout and formatting of build.gradle be as close tonAB-4's as possible, while preserving existing behavior.nnThis will make it easier to port over commits from AB-4.n
Rename directory `doc/` to `docs/`This makes it consistent with AB-4, making it easier to port overncommits from AB-4.n

Translate markdown files into asciidoc filesWe are going to convert all of our documentation from markdown tonasciidoc format, in order to take advantage of the additional featuresnand semantic elements that asciidoc offers such as automatic sectionnnumbering, admonitions and automatic table of contents (TOC) generation.nnUnfortunately, we have quite a lot of documents, and thus converting allnof these documents by hand is going to be extremely tedious.nnAs such, as a step towards the full conversion of our documentation tonasciidoc, let's enlist the help of pandoc[1] to translate ourndocumentation.nnThe translation is done with pandoc 2.2.1 via this shell script:nnfor x in $(find -name '*.md'); donpandoc -f markdown_github-hard_line_breaks --wrap=preserve --atx-headers -o ${x%*.md}.adoc $xndonennWhile the majority of the translation is done faithfully, there arenstill some errors here and there in the translated files. We will benfixing them in subsequent commits.nn[1] http://pandoc.org/n

Setup asciidoc-to-html build systemOur markdown documentation is published to GitHub pages via itsnautomatic markdown files publishing support[1]. However, this mechanismndoes not support asciidoc files.nnWe are in the process of converting all of our documentation tonasciidoc, so we'll need to setup our own GitHub pages build andndeployment system.nnLet's reuse the asciidoc-to-html build system in addressbook-level4[2]nby copying the relevant code/files.nn[1] https://github.com/blog/2289-publishing-with-github-pages-now-as-easy-as-1-2-3n[2] https://github.com/se-edu/addressbook-level4n

docs: fix heading levels to be consistentAsciidoctor complains with warnings when the heading levels are notnconsistent (e.g. a heading with level 4 when the heading directly abovenit is of level 2).nnLet's make asciidoctor happy by fixing the heading levels.n
docs: automatically generate table of contentsManually maintaining a table of contents is tedious, so let's replace itnwith an automatically generated one.n
docs: don't manually specify numbers in numbered listsThis reduces the number of required modifications when we wish to insertnan item in the middle of the list.n

docs: add images backAs in the markdown files, the images were specified using HTML ntags, pandoc did not recognize them and left them out when convertingnthe markdown files to asciidoc format.nnLet's add these images back to the adoc files.n

docs: replace links with cross-referencesInternal links using HTML anchors can only be used with asciidoctor'snhtml backends.nnLet's use asciidoctor's cross-reference syntax, which allows ourndocument's internal links to be supported in other backends.n

LearningOutcomes.adoc: fix links to source codeThese links only work when the document is viewed via github.com's reponbrowser.nnFrom se-edu.github.io, these links will point to non-existent locations.nnFix these links by defining an attribute, `repoURL`, to reducenrepetition, and fixing the links to use `repoURL`.n

AddressBook: remove master tag listWe keep track of a master tag list which holds all the tags innAddressBook.nnAs the master tag list was deemed unnecessary and may be too complexnfor new developers to grasp, as discussed innse-edu/addressbook-level4#753 and se-edu/addressbook-level4#794,nthe master tag list has already been removed in addressbook-level4nin se-edu/addressbook-level4#825. As such, the master tag listnshould also be removed here for consistency.nnLet's remove the master tag list in AddressBook.nnSimilarly, it is now unnecessary for AdaptedAddressBook to storena master tag list as well.nnLet's remove the master tag list in AdaptedAddressBook.n

Remove UniqueTagList classMany methods in UniqueTagList, such as mergeFrom(UniqueTagList),nwere previously used by only the AddressBook for the master tag list.nnSince AddressBook does not use a master tag list anymore, all thesenmethods are no longer necessary. UniqueTagList now only serves to addncomplexity to the code base.nnLet's remove the UniqueTagList class, and update Person to use a Setninstead for holding its tags instead, since it can only contain uniquenelements.n

docs: update component on UniqueTagListAddressBook previously had a UniqueTagList linked to it as thenmaster tag list, which was reflected in the architecture diagramsnin the DeveloperGuide and LearningOutcomes.nnSince AddressBook does not use a master tag list anymore, andnUniqueTagList has been removed, these architecture diagrams are nonlonger consistent with the program.nnLet's update these architecture diagrams in the DeveloperGuidenand LearningOutcomes.n

[#383] AddressBook: remove master tag list (#385)We keep track of a master tag list which holds all the tags inrnAddressBook.rnrnAs the master tag list was deemed unnecessary and may be toorncomplex for new developers to grasp, as discussed inrnse-edu/addressbook-level4#753 and se-edu/addressbook-level4#794,rnthe master tag list has already been removed in AB4rnby se-edu/addressbook-level4#825.rnrnUniqueTagList was also deemed unnecessary and removed inrnaddressbook-level4 after the master tag list is removed.rnrnAs such, the master tag list and UniqueTagList class should also bernremoved in the lower level projects.rnrnLet's remove the master tag list in AddressBook and AdaptedAddressBook,rnas well as the UniqueTagList class.rnrn  [1/3] AddressBook: remove master tag listrn  [2/3] Remove UniqueTagList classrn  [3/3] docs: update component on UniqueTagList

Storage: add AddressBookEncoder and AddressBookDecoder classesStorage uses the JAXB module for storing and retrieving of thenaddress book data in a file.nnHowever, we are trying to ensure Java 9 compatibility in #381,nbut the JAXB module is deprecated from Java 9 onwards.nnAs use of deprecated modules is considered bad practice, we shouldnreplace our storage needs with another library before moving onnto ensure Java 9 compatiblity.nnAs suggested here[1], let's reuse the storage code fromnaddressbook-level1.nnTo do this, let's create new classes, AddressBookEncoder andnAddressBookDecoder, which contains the ported storage code fromnaddressbook-level1, and update StorageFile to use them.nn[1]: https://github.com/se-edu/addressbook-level2/pull/382#issuecomment-409441789n

Fix runtests scripts proceeding on compilation error (#391)Runtests scripts compile the program under test, before executing therntests. The tests always execute regardless of whether the compilationrnsucceeds or not.rnrnIf the program has compilation errors, the runtests scripts arernactually testing an older version of the program without the errors.rnThis results in misleading test results.rnrnLet's teach the scripts to terminate immediately when the program failsrnto compile.

Developer Guide: Fix spelling errorSpelling of ClearCommand was incorrect in Design.nnLet's correct the spelling.n

Add netlify.tomlWe use Netlify to build and host deploy previews of our documentationnfor our PRs. Currently, Netlify is configured to build our documentationnusing the command ./gradlew asciidoctor.nnWithout a netlify.toml file in our repo, only the Nelify account ownerncan change that command, which is inconvenient.nnLet's add a netlify.toml file to the repo, so that any committer to thenrepo can change the Netlify configuration.n

Remove Gradle wrapperOur repo contains the Gradle wrapper to ensure that the correct Gradlenversion is used when we are building our documentation with asciidoctor.nnHowever, IntelliJ has a strange quirk where if:nn  * The project is imported by Create Project from existing Sources,nand,nn  * The `gradle-wrapper.jar` in the repo is selected as a libraryn(which is done by default)nnthen IntelliJ might end up marking the `src` directory as not a sourcesnroot directory, resulting in IntelliJ not being able to compile and runnthe project[1].nnWhile workarounds exists (such as telling users not to selectn`gradle-wrapper.jar` in the library selection stage), ultimately thisnboils down to the fact that we include the gradle wrapper in the reponeven though ordinary users won't be using it.nnSo, let's remove the Gradle wrapper in the repo.nnTo ensure that Travis/Netlify install and use the correct Gradlenversion, let's set up a system where Travis/Netlify will download thenGradle wrapper at build time. We are already hosting the Gradle wrappernof the version we want at https://se-edu.github.io/gradle-wrappernn[1] https://github.com/se-edu/addressbook-level1/commit/13daa30527fb541e6e7d073ec308537d1f21d871n

Rename `build.gradle` to `build.gradle.txt`We have a `build.gradle` file in the repo which tells Travis/Netlify hownto build our documentation with asciidoctor.nnHowever, when importing this repo as a project, IntelliJ will detect then`build.gradle` file and prompt the user with the following:nnUnlinked Gradle project?nnImport Gradle project, this will also enable Gradle Tool Window...nnThe correct action that should be taken by the user in this case isn_not_ to Import Gradle project, as this project is meant to be builtnwithout Gradle. However, this prompt may mislead the user into choosingnthe wrong thing.nnFix this by renaming `build.gradle` into `build.gradle.txt`. Keeping thenterm `build.gradle` in the filename will allow readers to easilynidentify the file as a `build.gradle` file, while the `.txt` extensionnwill make IntelliJ, and likely all other IDEs, stop identifying it as anGradle file (since text files, by definition, can contain anything).n

Hide Gradle from IntelliJ (#470)Since our project is meant to be built with IntelliJ, and withoutrnGradle, remove the Gradle wrapper and rename the `build.gradle` file torn`build.gradle.txt` so that IntelliJ won't think that we have a Gradlernbuild file in the repo.rnrn  [1/3] Add netlify.tomlrn  [2/3] Remove Gradle wrapperrn  [3/3] Rename `build.gradle` to `build.gradle.txt`

Utils#isAnyNull: Check for null on entire objectCurrently, isAnyNull assumes that the `items` varargs is not null.nnHowever, this is not necessarily the case. It can be the case thatn`isAnyNull(null)` is called. If the varargs is null, the function shouldnreturn false, since there is nothing to be examined. Presently, the codenwill simply crash with a NullPointerException if null is passed in as annargument.nnLet's add checks to ensure that the varargs object is not null.n

ParserTest: Fix incorrectly formatted command stringCurrently, the test methodsnparse_addCommandInvalidPersonDataInArgs_errorMessge() andnparse_addCommandInvalidArgs_errorMessage() use an incorrectly formattedncommand string. They attempt to format commands with `$s`.nnThis `$s` is not recognized by Javau00e2u0080u0099s String#format(u00e2u0080u00a6), thus thencommand is not formatted as expected, but instead simply left untouched.nThe tests currently pass, however, because `$s` achieves the purpose ofnbeing an invalid command string. However, this is clearly not thenintention of the test case, which is designed to simulate with samplennames, phones and emails.nnTo fix the bug in the test, letu00e2u0080u0099s change the occurrences of `$s` to `%s`.n

Rename `actual.txt` and `expected.txt` to all uppercaseOn Windows, when the case-sensitive attribute of the `test` directory isnset to `enabled` and `runtests.bat` is run, FC will report the followingnerror:nnFC: cannot open ACTUAL.TXT - No such file or foldernnThis is because FC internally transforms filenames to uppercase beforenopening them. Even though `runtests.bat` runs FC with the filenamesn`actual.txt` and `expected.txt`, FC will try to open the filesn`ACTUAL.TXT` and `EXPECTED.TXT` respectively. Usually this is not anproblem since file operations are case-insensitive by default onnWindows. However, when the `test` directory has the case-sensitivenattribute enabled, FC would fail to find those files, hence the error.nnThis results in developers being confused since `actual.txt` andn`expected.txt` exists in the `test` directory. In addition, they willnhave to resort to use other tools to compare the actual and expectednoutput of the program during testing.nnAlthough it is unlikely that developers enable the case attributenon the `test` directory intentionally, developers may accidentally do sonwithout realising. For instance, because directories created usingnWindows Subsystem for Linux (WSL) enables the case-sensitive attributenby default, when developers perform `git clone` on the repository undernWSL, all subdirectories (including `test`) created will have thencase-sensitive attribute set to `enabled` automatically.nnTo allow `fc` to open files in case-sensitive directories on Windowsnsuccessfully, let's rename `actual.txt` and `expected.txt` ton`ACTUAL.TXT` and `EXPECTED.TXT` respectively and update thendocumentation.n
